results.notes:
Growing gregariously, mostly in large fused clusters, under a sole white pine. Same organism/location as obs 149419 and obs 295576. Just a clonal variation of the more common form of weaverae (white stipes and pinkish-brown caps), but they look more like what was used to be called S. lactifluus, which was thought to be a NA taxon. However, Nguen et al. (2016) showed that American lactifluus collections synonymous with S. granulatus of Europe by DNA (both growing under hard pines). At the very least the former is not conspecific with what used to be called “granulatus” in the USA and is now called weaverae.
These have been growing in this spot like clockwork every year in late October, but for some strange reason they fruited in early September this year, when it was bone dry. Maybe the tree is stressed because the other pine and two other deciduous trees growing nearby were cut down in the spring. Other white pines elsewhere on the property didn’t produce any weaverae. Following this fruiting, there was one more 7-10 days later.
